description.text:
A standalone OpenSCAD library that allows you to create 1, 2 and 3 module size support frames, suitable for use with CBE covers and CBE and C-Link modules.

I designed this primarily because I wanted to build a custom touchscreen controller into my camper van and wanted it to match, as much as possible, the existing switches, sockets and so on that I'd been using. By making a printable and customisable frame, not only have I achieved this but I also realised that this was an opportunity to customise the look of all my existing CBE installation by using custom colours. In my case I have a bit of a red and black theme going on and printing red support frames and using CBE gloss black trims and modules matches my theme.

I've arranged the OpenSCAD source so that it can be included in your project and the frame can be created simply by calling support(). There are 2 optional parameters, the first is the number of modules (1, 2 or 3) and the second tells the library if it should include cutouts and supports for the modules. So, support(2, true); will create a 2 module frame with 2 cutouts and the appropriate locating pegs.

Everything can be adjusted using the variables at the top of the file, hopefully you'll be able to use it without modification though for most purposes.

This has now been updated to allow it to work with Customizer so you can adjust the primary options and produce your own .stl file.

This is a ping pong paddle from the president's trip to China to fix relation with Premier Chou En-Lai and helped with the establishment of Ping Pong Diplomacy.

Thing Information: Clues

1) This object is from the President's trip to China.
2) It originally had the presidents face on it.
3) The president was acting as chief diplomat to make a better relationship with China.

Thing Information: Significance and Research

The Object is a ping pong paddle. During this president's trip to China, he brought along ping pong democracy. He started a series of table tennis matched between American and Chinese players . This object has the face of the president while the other one had the face of Premier Chou En-Lai.

The President

The president was Richard Nixon, he served from 1969 to 1974 for the Republican Party.

Contribution, "The Act" and the President's role

President Nixon was serving as Chief Diplomat. His political was making a better relationship with China and bringing Ping Pong Diplomacy.
In 1972 President Nixon visited the People's Republic of China to try and make a better relationship with them. This is the beginning of Ping Pong Diplomacy. Before the tournament there were secret communications between American and Chinese players, the tournament was their first public encounter (Andrews 2016). By having the tournament it paved a way to open up discussions between the two countries. Our relationship with China now is more stable and they're one our major trading partners.

Impact/Significance on America

This object is important because it stands for when the president went to China to create a better relationship with them, they are now one our major trading partners and ally. I chose this artifact and president because it was for a very important time in American history and it helped the United States and China work together better.

Bibliography

Just a quick edit of the midskirt to make it easy to add another midhull and lift motor to the hovercraft. Print one of these, another midhull and another lift nacelle to drop in another motor.

I've not built it yet, but the idea is to add another counter-rotating lift motor to counteract the yaw induced by the single lift motor's torque. Then mix the lift channels into the rudder channel to add or subtract power from one or the other to give more yaw authority when moving slowly or not at all. It'll also be interesting to see if it's possible to move lift from front to back to balance the craft. With a 4s 5200mah battery hanging off the front of mine, it's quite nose heavy. Should also give us the option to mount the battery mid ship instead of on the nose. I'm not sure which way I want to mount the second midhull, there are two options pictured. Since the lift motor is not centered in the midhull, we can place them close together or further apart. I think further apart will give more yaw authority since the moments are further from the center of the craft? To add further complication, you can decide which way you want the skirts to glue to each other, changing the position of the air blowing straight down. In some orientations, you get 5 holes with the center most being tiny. In others, you get a larger center hole. It's up to you!
Stretched the midskirt along one axis to match the length of the midhull. The glue joints of the skirt do not match the glue joints of the hull. This is intentional.

description.text:
The Altoids Fishing Kit "catfisher" is my new ultra light fishing rig. I wanted to design another little fishing reel that is a bit more practical than my first one http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2002148. As the name suggests... you guessed it, the reel can be packed down into a standard Altoids tin and have some room to spare.

I added some metal hardware including nuts, bolts, and a 624 bearing so this one will not qualify as 100% printable. However, this should improve the usefulness and practicality of the design. With this new rig, mounting is simplified to use only one zip tie and there are fewer parts to print.

This reel is a basic hand crank spool with no drag or break for the drum (you need to use your thumb when casting) but I might upgrade that after I get a chance to do some more field testing. Due to the addition of the ball bearing this little reel can cast baits and lures that have a bit of weight so it should be well suited for back county catfish dinner on the open fire.

Use a 7" zip tie for the reel and 4” zip ties to fix the eye guides to a long flexible branch or piece river cane, and away you go!

Printer:

prusa i3 custom

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.3mm layers

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Print 3 eyes, the base and the pin with no support. I had to design the base part with it's own built in support material because it has some unsupported mass but the slicer software was generating some really weird support material that was impossible to detach from the part (see pics for details).

Print the inside spool, outside spool and the hub with support material for best results.

Clean Up the Parts

Remove the support material and clean up any burrs from the plastic parts. To clean up the base part, snip the 4 connections to the bottom arm. (remember that this part is designed with the support material integrated into the model) and cut through the little diagonal fins that support the top arm (see pics below). remove the chunk of support material and sand all the connection points with a bit of sand paper or emery cloth.

snip cut remove

Printed Parts

1 - Base
1 - Hub
1 - outside spool
1 - inside spool
1 - pin
3 - eyes

all parts Nuts and Bolts

1 - 4mm x 30mm bolt
1 - 4mm washer
1 - 4mm nylock nut
1 - 624 ball bearing (13mm diameter, 5mm wide, 4.5mm dia hole)
1 - 3mm x 30mm bolt
1 - 3mm x 20 mm bolt
3 - 3mm nuts
3 - 3mm washers

all hardware Misc Supplies

1 - altiods tin
1 - 7" zip tie
3 - 4" zip ties

    • optional glue that will be compatible with you filament of choice
Assembly: step 1

Fit the ball bearing into the inside spool.

Assembly: step 1

Insert the hub into the outside spool.

Assembly: step 3

Using the 4mm hardware, bolt the assembly together loosely. this is the part when you could add a bit of glue to the spool halves to make sure they stay put when you get a little tension on the line.

Assembly: step 4

Add the crank bolt and washer stuff and snug up all the hardware to your taste.

Assembly: step 4 (mounting)

Take the left over 3mm hardware and install the little pin. Adjust the pin to suit the diameter your particular fishing stick of choice (I used a pencil in the pic) and use a zip tie to mount it.
Wind on a bit of fishing line and your ready to go.

The power supply was missing a knob, so I printed a replacement.  The hole for the pot was too small, so I drilled it out and it's a nearly perfect friction fit!

My ultimaker suffered from the problems outlined in the ultimaker wiki with the loose holes on the delrin plastic blocks that the springy bed mounts on.  The holes were so loose that one stripped.  I measured the old one, drew it up, and printed.  voila!

A bit of a hack job; 2 problems: My printer shrinks holes - not sure if its the skein (Cura RC1) or calibration on the printer...and the model is about 3% too big to EASILY pop it into the wood, so I printed it at 95% rather than resizing the model (because the model is afaik the correct per my measurements).
Because of the shrinkyholes and the 'print at 95%', I had to make the center bore larger than it should be (almost 3.4mm) and it comes off the printer at around 2.8mm diameter - just small enough for the screw teeth to have something to bite into.
http://wiki.ultimaker.com/Ultimaker_rev.3_assembly:_Z-stage
-- they suggest putting a piece of paper down the bore with the screw - I figured since I have a 3d printer, do it properly! Long story short:
"Screwblock Large.stl" the one I use, 3rd on the right in the picture of 3
0.15mm layers
ABS (pla should be fine)
100% fill
2 walls @ .4mm nozzle (more is fine just they won't fit, ymmv).
95% scale "Screwblock original.stl" middle in the picture of 3
same settings, but you'll have to sand a few thou off the outside edges for it to fit in the machine, and maybe ream out the hole - depends on your printer.

This is a a customizer designed to create a laser cut template which will then be folded into a seedling planter. The planter is intended to be made of corrugated cardboard. Measure the thickness of the cardboard you will be using, and place that measurement in the file. This is intended to output a DXF file, so using it offline is necessary. Possibly based on demand I will create a printable one.

::The height and width are customizable. The program will automatically scale your drawing to 90% of the size of your printer bed (based on the dimensions you give it).
::The tabs are set to the thickness of your cardboard, so measure those.
::The tab angle kinda sets the compression necessary for a fit. Recommend 35-70 degrees.

Future Edits Might include:
-Different Tabs/methods of locking
-A printable mode
-Slight changes to the default file
-Making the file more idiot-proof (testing for bad cases of inputs)
-Instructions for an educational lesson plan

1) Remove the cutout from the die.
2) On the side that you want facing out, make 4 scores of the cardboard, around the middle "square". If using corrugated cardboard, as recommended, cut through the top paper, and the corrugations, but not the bottom paper.
3)Fold up the sides with the cutouts
4) Fold up the sides with the tabs, and press them into the cutouts.
5) Fill with dirt
6) Plant seeds or seedlings.
7) When ready to transplant, stick directly in the ground. AS long as it's kept moist, the cardboard will biodegrade.

title: Dial indicator mount for MP Select Mini

description.text:
For mounting a dial indicator to the extruder head for precision bed leveling.

How to use it:

Step 1: Home the axis

Step 2: Turn off the printer. You don't want to move the extruder with the controls, the dial will hit the tower before the extruder hits the limit switch.

Step 3: Manually move the extruder away from the tower so there's room for the dial.

Step 4: Remove the fan and insert the dial so that the tabs slide into the slots in the back of the heatsink. Be careful not to put force into the gantry, you do not want to bend that.

Step 5: Raise the bed by turning the screw nearest to the extruder, this should be the front left screw, until the dial stops turning (or slows down significantly). This is the point where the extruder makes contact with the bed. Zero the dial here.

Step 6: Lower the bed until the dial is at 4 thou or 0.1mm. Manually move the extruder and lift the contact stick thing between stops, this keeps it from jiggling around and possibly pushing itself up (not necessary for a glass bed since it's smoother). You can swich it back on and move it with the controls so you can get a continuous view of the level, just be careful not to let it crash into the tower. Do this for all 4 corners, halfway points between the corners, and it's also a good idea to check the center.

Then you're done! You may find that your bed is slightly high in the middle, try to even it out by lowering the corners a thou or two. It could take a couple laps around the perimeter before all 4 corners are level, so just keep going until it's good. You may have more uncompensatable runoff than you were expecting, mine is about 0.2mm but it still prints fine.

Like most people, my build plate on my HICTOP 3DP-11-AL (3DP-12) was fairly badly bowed down in the middle and was a little worse in the front than in the back. This results in pretty poor 'auto-leveling' using the inductive sensor. Updating firmware to include bilinear (mesh) leveling helped some, but the bowing effect could still be observed. I designed this piece to sit underneath the build plate on the carriage, and push up just slightly to minimize bowing. The smaller pieces are just twisted into the cutouts in the build plate (they don't twist in all the way, which is fine) and contain an M3 nut. An M3 bolt through both of these support the "bar" which sits across them. The level of the support bar can be adjusted by turning the bolts. Place the smallers pieces nearer the front of the cutouts if the build plate is more bowed in the front than in the back. Debugging output of sensor height during autoleveling clearly shows improvements. I did some really fast prints and at different temperatures and saw little movement, though its clearly possible for the M3 bolt to back off. Updating to a nylock nut or putting springs in could help that if it ends up being a problem.

Printed in ABS to be able to handle exposure to the build plate, but I never go above PLA (~70C) on my build plate.

title: Nerf Explosive Tips - Party Snap Foam Dart Tips

description.text:
For some added explosive fun during your next Nerf War, I've made a 3D printable replacement tip for foam darts that holds "party snaps" that explode on impact!

The tips are made to leave about 1-2mm of the "party snap" exposed at the tip while holding the snap securely for active Nerf play. I've tested the darts up to 50 feet away from a smooth surface (garage door) and they still explode on impact. I've tested well over a hundred rounds and haven't had a single jam as the tip fits perfectly with the foam dart.

Disclaimer: I ADVISE THAT YOU DO NOT SHOOT THESE AT PEOPLE OR ANIMALS

I tested these with PLA, PETG, and TouchInk (a semi-flexible filament) and the best results were with PLA.

Now available: Explosive Tips for your MEGA Nerf Darts: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2156994

For instructions and testing results, please view the video at: https://youtu.be/stezC9FAD3E

And, for the best quality results with quick cleanup:

Carefully remove the tip from a standard Nerf bullet/foam dart (the generic versions are usually easier to pull apart than genuine Nerf darts). Screw in the tip you printed. Slip a "Party Snap" into the hole. Load the dart and fire!

Check the YouTube video for more instructions and the testing results of the Nerf Explosive Tips!

description.text:
Pocket grapple based on a YouTube video I saw.

It is intended to hang from a cord for picking up small items. It also makes a good fidget.

  • Version two is more my own design, and a little more steam-punk. Designed to be printer at 0.25mm layer height.
  • I have updated the screws so they are stronger and only partially threaded.
  • I added a new version with a hollow screw for a cord, in place of the U-strap.
  • The holes in the tip of the hook are for a small lead weight or BB for weight.
  • The assembled version is just an example, it is not designed to be printed.
  • Vertically printed screws are awesome, but not very strong. If you have any 6mm nylon screws, I would use them. :)

description.text:
Bought an adapter from PhoneSkope.com to use your GoPro Hero 3+/4 and ended up buying a Hero 5 Black later, only to be upset that Phone Skope doesn't sell an adapter for the Hero 5? Don't want to have to print out my entire GoPro Hero 5 Black Scope / Optic Adapter and really only need a little adapter to use your Hero 5 with your current plate? Well, you're in luck today! This should work with any other GoPro Hero 3+/4 accessories where you use a friction fit of the case's lens to mount the camera.

Designed in Fusion 360, but I'm not including the F360 file as I don't think it's needed. The external dimensions are 36.3mm x 33.8mm with a corner radius of 3.5mm. The Hero 5's lens dimensions are 32mm x 28.75mm with a corner radius of 5mm. I then offset that 1.9mm to create a hard stop for the lens. It's extruded 5.5mm (the stop is only 1mm).

Pretty simple stuff here, folks. I hope this solves a problem for you! Enjoy!

description.text:
Have you ever worried about leaving your printer running for those long 20 hour prints? With a heated bed, hot extruder, and cheap power supply, there's a lot that could go wrong. I have worried about leaving my printer unattended and wanted an automatic smoke detection and shutdown solution. This post contains all the information you need to build a 3D Printer Safety Shutdown. I am not selling anything. This is merely the information needed to make your own printer shutdown device.

This solution uses an IOT Power Relay from Digital-Loggers.com which has an input that can turn the IOT Power Relay strip on or off with a low voltage signal. The IOT Relay also has a "Normally On" pair of receptacles and a "Normally Off" pair of receptacles. The IOT Power Relay control connector is connected to an off the shelf First Alert Dual Mode Smoke Detector which has an output that can trigger other smoke detectors. The First Alert Dual Mode Smoke Detector is a very sophisticated dual smoke detector that is far better than the Arduino smoke sensors that some people are using to build safety off devices. That trigger output is used to turn off the IOT Control Relay. The power will stay off only as long as the smoke detector senses smoke so I added a feature to latch the off action. I did this by adding a 5V wall transformer to the "Normally OFF" side of the IOT Relay. That wall transformer powers up when the printer has been shut off and keeps the input to the IOT Relay in the off state.

For safety reasons I powered the Smoke Detector with its own 3.3V wall transformer to avoid having 110 VAC in the circuit. You can use a second 5V transformer with 3 power diodes to drop the voltage to 3V. To connect power to the smoke detector, solder wires to the battery tabs inside the battery compartment. One of the photos shows a pictorial wiring diagram of the design. This device uses two power diodes to provide an "OR" function between the smoke detector output and the 5V wall transformer output. In other words "Keep power off if Smoke is detected OR the 5V wall transformer is on". The diodes block the current flow from conflicting as the device switches from the smoke detector holding the power off to the wall transformer holding the power off.

The design works smoothly and requires no Arduino, software, or special parts. The wall transformers can be old cell phone chargers. The total cost for IOT Control Relay and smoke detector is about $50. Add another $15 if you have to buy the wall transformers and power diodes. I’ve included a smoke detector spacer ring which allows the cable to exit on a flush mount installation such as under a shelf.

Here are links to the parts needed:
Power Control Strip - IOT Power Relay
https://www.adafruit.com/products/2935
https://www.amazon.com/Iot-Relay-Enclosed-High-power-Raspberry/dp/B00WV7GMA2

Smoke Detector - First Alert BRK 3120B
https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00O8MVW44
5V Wall Transformers
https://www.amazon.com/ZIUMIER-100-240V-Connector-Switching-Transformer/dp/B01MA5BAC2
Two 1A Power Diodes
https://www.amazon.com/FAIRCHILD-SEMICONDUCTOR-1N4001-STANDARD-pieces/dp/B00LQPUOHW

I present this design as a "USE AT YOUR OWN RISK" solution. I believe that it is safe and relaible. I have been using it in my home for about a year. I occasionally test my detector to make sure it is working. One match proves that my 3D printer will shutdown with just a wisp of smoke.

Here's a video showing the 3D Printer Safety Shutdown in action. The video shows that the device shuts the printer off after just a wisp of smoke and that the smoke detector doesn't continue to blare. The smoke detector also shuts off after doing its job. It is easy to reset the power and the smoke detector by cycling power to the IOT Relay.

3D Printer Safety Shutdown
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=P-1EX5GqZd4

What can happen without a safety shutdown:
http://forums.reprap.org/read.php?392,294850
https://all3dp.com/fire-safety-unattended-3d-printer-nearly-burns-house-down

Update Sept 9, 2017: Data Loggers has redesigned the IOT Relay which is thankfully available again. They changed one of the switched Normally "ON" outlets to be an "ON" always outlet. You can still use this design. Plug the Smoke detector wall transformer into the "ON" always outlet. The only difference with the newer IOT Relay is that the Smoke Detector will continue blaring until the smoke has cleared. The printer will still stay off as it did previously.

Update Fe 10, 2018: It is acceptable to power the smoke detector with 110 VAC. It can be plugged into the "always on" outlet of the IOT Relay. I didn't suggest this in the original design because it requires 110V in the circuit which some people may not be comfortable with assembling.

If your a "child of the 80s" like me you probably remember the movie Crocidile Dundee, and it's Sequel. In the second movie Mic Dundee goes up on the side of a mountain and makes a "telephone call" to all the locals. He uses a Bullroar which is something the aborigines have been using for hundreds of years. It produces a thrumming noise kinda like the prop of a cessna airplane.
I tried carving one of these a long time ago and while it did sort of work it wasn't as nice as I had hoped. So A couple weeks ago i found my original carved one and decided to model it and print a new one. It does work (although not a loud as in the movie). A teacher could easily use this as an experiment as there is a lot of science and math that could be involved. Firt, how many middle sections do you need to print, secondly how much rope do you need to get the maximum sound etc. a word of warning you might want to wear a leather glove when you try it the first time. you will rub a blister on your rope hand if you don't.

• Print 1 top, 1 bottom and as many middles as you want.
  • Super glue them together.
  • tie a sturdy chord or rope to the top. You will need at least 2-3 feet of rope. make sure your chord is strong stuff. Even though this thing is light as a feather it will still have some pretty good force pulling on it.
  • take out side to a nice open area. Swing the bullroar in FAST circles at your side. The speed you swing with and the ocassional movement of the rope in your hand will eventually cause it to start to thrum.
  • Start up a BBQ because you just invited all your mates over. :c)

Cheap HALL OMNIDIRECTIONAL magnetic endstop - Only TWO components, sub $2*

I used the Honeywell SS451A - omnidirectional switch so you don't need to bother with magnet direction, hall switch (not ratiometric), Supply voltage 3 to 24V; only additional part is a 10k pull-up resistor (according to Honeywell installation instructions).
*Cost = US $1.92/piece or 10 for US $11.87 or US $1.18/piece. (DigiKey part number 480-3587-ND) anyway sub $2.50. THIS IS IMPORTANT!!! Use a SMALL, TINY magnet. This will address the 'hysteresis.' Hall sensors typically have different grip and release parameters, for instance 135G Trip, -120G Release for mine; the smaller size the magnetic field, the less important this becomes. See the pics above to get an idea. The sensor sinks current when tripped, so you need to invert the AXIS logic, I use Marlin with RAMPS, so it looks like this in line 233 of configuration.h: "const bool Z_ENDSTOPS_INVERTING = true;" for the Z stop, etc. Sorry for the hack solder job, but the cost of a PCB would break the $2 mark. You can also add an LED if you want between the V+ and out pins with 250ohm limiting resistor.

Hey,

I'm happy to offer you my first fidget/skill toy of the following AP-Collection!
It's a Begleri skill toy inspired by a google search and this design: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2098717

If you don't know what this should be: https://youtu.be/4yZC1inesPY

I redesigned it to make it easy to change the length of the cord and the weights of the beads. I also added the possibility to put magnets (5x2mm) in so the beads can stick to each other if you don't use the begleri.

In the files you'll find two versions:

AP-SuperBegleri: One is my final version with all the features and threaded parts to change length and weight. This design is a bit tricky to print so use your finest settings ;)
